<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05179c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05179c">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05179c"> 179(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <font color="green">[Smutsongs]</font> hide heads in / Welsh ditches</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"> Other airs are not so fortunate. Partnered by vulgar or meaningless or dissolute words, they drop out of favour, and many of these are at this very moment <mark>hiding their heads among the Welsh vales</mark> and mountains. Even Moore&apos;s instinct was not unerring, and some of his melodies have ceased to hold the public, because the words written to the airs have proved to be of an ephemeral kind. <small> Alfred Perceval Graves, <a name="ILMS" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ILMS"><cite title="source">Irish Literary and Musical Studies</cite></a>, (1913) [Folk Song] 184</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
